### Flake-parts Integration Example

To integrate `treefmt-nix` with `flake-parts`, you need to import `treefmt-nix.flakeModule` into your `flake-parts` configuration and define a `perSystem.treefmt` block .

Here's a full `flake.nix` example:

```nix
# flake.nix
{
  inputs = {
    nixpkgs.url = "github:nixos/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";
    flake-parts.url = "github:hercules-ci/flake-parts";
    treefmt-nix.url = "github:numtide/treefmt-nix";
  };

  outputs = { self, nixpkgs, flake-parts, treefmt-nix, ... }:
    flake-parts.lib.mkflake {
      imports = [
        treefmt-nix.flakeModule # 1. Import the flakeModule
      ];
      systems = [ "x86_64-linux" "aarch64-linux" ]; # Define your supported systems

      perSystem = { pkgs, config, system, ... }: {
        # 2. Configure treefmt within perSystem
        treefmt = {
          projectRootFile = "flake.nix"; # File to determine the project root
          programs.nixpkgs-fmt.enable = true; # Enable a formatter, e.g., nixpkgs-fmt
          # You can add more programs and settings here
          # programs.terraform.enable = true;
          # settings.formatter.terraform.excludes = [ "hello.tf" ];
        };

        # The formatter and checks are automatically set by the flakeModule
        # config.formatter will be set to config.treefmt.build.wrapper
        # config.checks.treefmt will be set to config.treefmt.build.check self
      };
    };
}
```  

### `treefmt.build.wrapper`

The `treefmt.build.wrapper` option provides a wrapped `treefmt` executable that includes your specified configuration . This wrapper is automatically set as the `formatter` output for your flake when `flakeFormatter` is enabled . When you run `nix fmt`, this wrapper is invoked to format your project files according to the `treefmt` configuration .

The wrapper script handles finding the project root and passing the generated `treefmt.toml` configuration to the `treefmt` binary .

### `treefmt.build.check`

The `treefmt.build.check` option creates a flake check that verifies if your project's code is already formatted . This check is automatically added to your flake's `checks` output under `checks.<system>.treefmt` when `flakeCheck` is enabled . Running `nix flake check` will execute this check, and it will fail if any files are not formatted according to your `treefmt` configuration . The check works by copying the project, initializing a git repository, running `treefmt`, and then checking for any changes using `git diff --exit-code` .

## Notes

The `flake-parts` integration is the most streamlined method for projects already using `flake-parts` . It automatically wires the `formatter` and `checks` outputs based on the `flakeFormatter` and `flakeCheck` options, which default to `true` . The `projectRootFile` defaults to `"flake.nix"` in the `flake-parts` module .

